A bone house still fascinates after 100 years. Look at Gaudi’s interiors
The roof mutes like the back of a prehistoric oak, the stairs like the spine of a dinosaur and the balconies are broken fish muzzles.
This is the Casa Batlló of Catalan architect Antonio Gaudi in Barcelona.
The house, with its organic forms, received the nickname "Knochenhaus" from its inhabitants.
Organic shapes, wild colors, the unusual use of stone, tile fragments and mosaics, the facades reminiscent of sheds and ubiquitous soft lines, all these are typical features of Antonio Gaudi's art style.
The façade of the house plays with dreamlike lines, delicate colours and textures reminiscent of nature and living beings.
It is only with a closer look that we notice that everything is dominated by geometry, rhythm and thoughtful order.
During the night, the entire façade still acts more plastic, more dramatic and the special illumination enhances the shine of the colors.
The same swinging lines and devoured shapes also dominate the interior of the house.
Wave-shaped wood copies the window frames, railings, decorative elements of doors, even hatches and bars.
The house Batlló in the Eixample district on the busy shopping street Passeig de Grácia No. 43 was built by the reconstruction of a house from 1877, which was executed by the architect Emilio Sala Cortese.
The reconstruction took two years and was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrial Josep Batlló, originally insisted on the demolition of the old and the construction of a completely new building, but ultimately he agreed with Gaudí's idea of an unusual and also cheaper conversion.
The Casa Batlló rental house, however, did not design Antoni Gaudí alone.
He worked with architect Josep Maria Jujol.
The decorations for the representative home of the real estate owner were created on his drawing board, and the use of mosaics on the facade was his idea.
However, numerous other artists and artists participated in the design of the façade.
The joint work on the drafts for Casa Batlló was the beginning of a fruitful cooperation between Jujola and Gaudí.
Jujol also participated in the construction of Gaudí's Casa Milá house in Güell Park, where other works by Antoni Gaudí are also located.
Shortly after its completion, the house was given by the local inhabitants of its organic forms because of the nickname "Knochenhaus".
Others, in turn, called it the special window opening mechanism because of the "gendering house".
It is also said that the sword of St. George, the Patron of Catalonia, is represented at the top of the building.
But other sculptural elements also symbolize hidden religious motives.
Gaudí designed for the house a central heating system unique for the time with ventilation channels and typical fireplaces.
A little bit bizarre already reminds me of her 45 degree inclination.
In his work Gaudí consistently ignored all the building regulations at the time and was not allowed to get involved in any of these.
Before the construction began, he obtained the appropriate building permission from the city, but the information he had provided on the planned reconstruction was so vague that the city fathers two years later were so shocked by the result that they demanded compensation.
Among other things, the councillors also felt that the construction with its pillars even intervened in the public side.
However, there were no changes, quite the contrary - only fifteen days after the district's invitation to do so, Josep Batlló submitted an application for the lease of the two upper floors of the house - and it was given to him promptly.
The owner himself moved into the lower floors.
In the gallery on the 2nd floor there was a social salon, on the 3rd floor were the bedrooms and private rooms of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewelry store.
The entire six-storey building runs through a staircase up to the roof terrace.
Due to the basic elements of the reconstruction, all right angles and straight lines were removed and replaced by curved and curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with a modern concept for connecting rooms.
The social part can be completely connected by opening the salon doors and so a larger society could chat comfortably, without having to refrain from a certain intimacy in more confidential conversations.
In addition to a new façade, Gaudí’s conversion also gave the house a rather unusual roof and two other floors.
Gaudí's play with light as well as the blue and white glazed tiles, with which the inner courtyard is clothed and the light courts, is impressive.
The play of these two colours gives all floors of the house a maximum of light.
He simply used the principle that white reflects light better than dark colors that absorb sunlight on the contrary.
The Casa Batlló House, which was included in the UNESCO World Heritage List in 2005, can be visited today by anyone.
On the first floor the most spacious and magnificent apartment is made accessible to the public.
The homeowners decided only in the year to take this step on the occasion of the 150th birthday of the famous Creator.
When one found that this is quite acceptable business, one kept the visits, yes they also extended them to other common and attic rooms, including the roof terrace.
The price for visiting the building monument, however, is not a cardboard stake; it amounts to 16.50 euros, students, pensioners, groups and holders of tourist cards get 20 percent discount.
This amount exceeds the entry prices for other Gaudí buildings in the city.
If you would like to get to know the real atmosphere of the house with its dragon towers, try to make friends with one of the housemates and visit him at home.
