A longer index finger than a ring finger means a lower risk of cancer
Men whose index finger is longer than the ring finger are obviously at a lower risk of developing prostate cancer.
This is the surprising result of a study published on Wednesday by the British Journal of Cancer.
This is to be related to the mirror of the male hormone testosterone.
"Our results show that the relative length of the fingers can serve as a simple test for the risk of prostate cancer, particularly in men up to sixty," the co-author of the study, Ros Eeles, Professor at the Cancer Research Institute at the University of Warwick, explained.
The finger could help to determine which men should be subject to a prostate cancer test, especially when genetic risks or other risk factors exist, such as family health burdens, Ms. Eeles added.
During the period 1994-2009, she and her colleagues in Britain followed more than 1500 patients with prostate cancer, but also 3000 healthy men.
For more than half of the participants in the study, the index finger was shorter on the right hand than the ring finger.
For these men, the probability of prostate cancer was the same as for 19 percent of men whose ring and finger fingers were the same.
However, in men whose index finger was longer than the ring finger, this risk fell by 33 percent, in men by up to sixty by 87 percent.
The ratio of the length of the two mentioned fingers, which are already in prenatal age, clearly reflects the different mirrors of sex hormones to which the child was exposed in the uterus.
Less testosterone corresponds to a longer index finger.
Previous research has shown that testosterone is accelerating the growth of prostate cancer.
Václav Pačes, a leading Czech geneticist and former chairman of the Academy of Sciences, said ČTK that he was well-known for this study, but he still does not consider the relationship between the length of his fingers and the risk of cancer "overall".
