The democratic movement in Latin America is becoming stronger, as is the support of private companies.
Crime is a bigger problem than unemployment.
In many parts of the region, Brazil's influence is greater than that of the United States.
These were the results of the Latinobarómetro survey, which was conducted in 18 countries and published exclusively in The Economist.
This survey has been conducted on a regular basis since 1995 and shows the exchange of views in this region.
Two facts are particularly relevant in this year's September and October survey.
First, the good atmosphere in Latin America
and secondly, the growing interest in democracy and its most important institutions.
In many countries on the Pacific coast of South America, the democratic movement has increased sharply (see Table 1).
In Peru, for example, where the economy has grown by about 6% annually since 2002, the number of advocates for democracy rose from 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
Even in Mexico, where the economy has recovered since the strong collapse of last year, such a trend can be seen.
But only half of the respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the region's most populous countries, are convinced democrats, which lowers the regional average (see Chart 2).
Approximately 44% of the respondents stated that they were satisfied with the democratic practice of their country, as much as in last year, but 25% more than in 2001 (Figure 3).
About 34% trust the Congress of their country and 45% their government. Both values correspond to those of last year, but show a significant increase compared to 2003 (17% and 24% respectively).
A decade ago, Latin America's economic crisis undermined efforts to increase democracy.
The fact that this continued during the global economic crisis may be due to the fact that Latin American countries experienced only a short recession and recovered quickly.
Moreover, the poor were caught up by a stronger social network.
(According to reports by the UN Economic Commission for Latin America this week, the poverty rate in Latin America has increased only marginally in 2009 and again by 32% this year.)
However, there are strong differences in mood from country to country (see Chart 4).
Brazil's strong economy and the popularity of the outgoing President, Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva, are reflected in a widespread sense of progress.
In Mexico and Central America, where the recession was more noticeable and violent crimes have increased, this is less the case.
Only for the second time since the survey began, many respondents in Latin America see criminality in their country as a bigger problem than unemployment (see Chart 5).
About 31% say that either they themselves or a family member were victims of a crime last year. However, compared with 38% last year, the values have fallen and thus reached the lowest level since 1995.
The increase in economic performance is reflected in the stronger support for the private and market economy: about 71% of the respondents on regional level indicated that the private sector is indispensable for development; in 2007 it was 56% (see Chart 6).
