Sport and regulation
Tricks like those of Alonso and Ramos in the game against the Ajax show the spirit of invention, but not the will to avoid a sanction.
The alleged exclusion of two players from the Real Madrid (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the game on November 23rd against the Ajax in the Champions League led to a lot of ink being shed on whether it was an unsports act or not and whether or not both players should be sanctioned by UEFA.
As is well known, the two players lost time a few minutes before playing (their team had already clearly won) and played several Fouls so that the referee showed them the second yellow card.
In this way, and since Real Madrid would lead its group, the two players will meet the required penalty for the next league game against Auxerre and thus enter the next game phase without any cards.
Finally, the Disciplinary Committee of UEFA punished the club's coach, José Mourinho, with two games and the players involved with different amounts of money.
The provocation of a yellow card under such or similar circumstances is not a new practice, it is more often found in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos - the unwritten rules, but followed in this sport.
Part of the debate on the case presented is that a team of the Real Madrid football club (who, in his hymn, proclaims the nobleness and honour and on other occasions has punished his players for similar incidents) played the main role in this, and on the dramatization by Mourinho, who added an episode more to his long history than theatrical and provocative technicians.
In any case, the debate is about whether this practice, which is not explicitly prohibited by the Statutes, contradicts the principles of sport, i.e. whether these actions constitute a change in the rules. In fact, this practice adheres to the Statutes of Sport, but seems to bypass its meaning.
In this case, the damage caused to the sports spirit should be investigated.
The sports spirit defends the physical integrity of the opponents, an aspect that was not compromised by these actions, because it was not an aggressive game.
Another aspect of a clean game is to avoid that the competing players derive an unjustified benefit from the counterteam. Nor did that happen.
The paradox of the action of the players of Real Madrid is that it does not correspond to what we normally understand by miscarriage or miscarriage, because the bypassing of the rule was not secretly carried out to avoid a sanction, but should be as conspicuous as possible to punish it by the referee.
The players waited and gladly accepted the penalty.
Another question is, what kind of advantage the infringers drew from the deliberate fols.
Here, it should be stressed that the rival was neither brought into a more unfavourable position nor raised advantages for the game played, because the obvious result of this action was that his team had to continue playing with fewer players.
It is also not a useful strategy for the next game, because the club does not have these players.
The advantage is clearly that players start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future game.
But it is a long-term, up to a certain degree unknown advantage, as the team could eventually quit. Furthermore, the players with this procedure receive a penalty and pass into the second card cycle, in which they quit less because of card accumulation than in the first cycle.
This makes it not so clear whether it really is an advantage.
In the end, such practices are not directed against the spirit of sport, which also includes strategic decisions to derive the greatest possible benefit from the rules.
In this case, the players did not want to avoid a sanction (which would actually be a clear case of rule-by-rule confusion), they rather wanted to choose when they would be subject to it.
They made a strategic decision without avoiding punishment or fleeing from it.
Although the boundary between invention and the regulatory environment is blurred, I believe that this issue is a clear case of invention.
I have the impression that the polemics came from two factors: because it was two self-exclusions and because of the kind of provoked rule transfer.
The damage that these actions have done to the principles of sport is less ethical than aesthetic.
