The US changes the rules for obtaining a visa
The persons must present themselves to the visa application offices prior to their discussions at the consulate; the costs will be reduced in such a way.
From 10 January 2011, the procedures for applying for a visa will change in the United States Embassy and consulates.
In the new procedure, most applicants must present themselves to the Visa Application Offices (ASC, the initial letters in English) prior to their discussions in the consulate.
The staff of the ASC shall record the biometric data of the applicant which are checked by the consulate before the conversation.
The new method has certain advantages for the aspirants, including:
The total cost of processing the visa will decrease, as it will no longer be necessary to pay separately the deadline, the processing of the visa application and the transport service with which the document is handed over.
The applicant makes only one payment covering the three services.
The current price remains unchanged: the counter-claim of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for a visa with a request (including a visa for temporary workers) and $390 for hands and investors.
Those who only want to extend their visa must not have a conversation in the consulate, they must only present themselves at the nearest ASC, where they will present their documents and take their fingerprints.
Since biometric data are collected in the ASC, applicants who need a second date for the conversation in the consulate remain there for less time than before.
Those applying for a visa in the consulates of Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo do not have to pay for the 26-dollar service surcharge.
More information on the new visa application procedure can be found at: http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
