According to yesterday's plan, the main problem would be avoided in the form of 1.8 billion tonnes (Gt) of CFCs delivered to the earth due to lighting, if the white glowing pears, which still represent a monopoly of 50 to 70% on the market so far, were replaced by fluorescent or better light-emitting diodes (LEDs).
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
This corresponds to an equivalent of 70% of the emissions of the global fleet.
In Copenhagen last year, major emissions emitters such as the United States, China, Europe, and others, including Canada, committed to voluntary reduction plans that would lower global CFC emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
From this balance sheet, however, it would be necessary to deduct 5 gt from the balance sheet in order to stabilise the rise in climate by 2 degrees Celsius from today to 2020 in order to prevent it from being out of control.
In the white glowing pears 95% of the energy escapes in the form of heat, and the remaining 5% produce the light.
With compact light bulbs the energy consumption is reduced by 75%, with the new LED bulbs reducing this energy requirement again by twice.
On average, the compact light bulbs last between 6000 and 10,000 hours.
The new LED bulbs, such as those that the Philips manufacturer put on the market this week - this company, by the way, has participated in the UN study - have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than a whitish bulb, which conveys an indication of the savings potential of the exchange plan to be applied in 100 countries.
