Several specialists have shown that compact light bulbs have reserves because they contain mercury and that they must therefore be disposed of as special waste, which is not always possible in developing countries except producers provide an acceptance centre.
However, according to the report, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not the compact light bulb, but rather the coal-fired power plants, which emit much more mercury to produce the electricity wasted by the white-flowered bulbs.
In the United States alone, these coal power stations emit 25,000 tonnes of mercury annually.
The report sets out in detail the profits that each country would gain from this international programme.
